{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523299"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:54:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:54:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13889"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13889","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13889"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.08,0.05,0.79,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6508"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49032"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6508"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13889"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34053"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"354"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12966"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12967"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49032","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49032"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 61-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a five-year history of progressive difficulty swallowing both solids and liquids. He reports regurgitation of undigested food and occasional chest pain after eating. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. A chest X-ray is performed as part of the initial workup (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most pertinent finding present in this chest X-ray?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Air-fluid level in the stomach","Retrosternal goitre","Hilar lymphadenopathy","Dilated oesophagus","Deviated trachea"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most pertinent finding present in this chest X-ray is a \u003Cstrong\u003Edilated oesophagus\u003C/strong\u003E. This is a characteristic radiographic finding in advanced achalasia, which is the most likely diagnosis based on the clinical presentation. Achalasia is a motility disorder of the oesophagus characterized by impaired relaxation of the lower oesophageal sphincter and loss of peristalsis in the distal oesophagus. This leads to progressive dysphagia to both solids and liquids, as seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eair-fluid level in the stomach\u003C/strong\u003E is not a typical finding in achalasia and would not be the most pertinent observation in this case. While gastric air-fluid levels can be seen on chest X-rays, they are not specifically associated with oesophageal disorders.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eretrosternal goitre\u003C/strong\u003E can cause compression of the oesophagus and trachea, potentially leading to dysphagia and respiratory symptoms. However, it is not the most likely cause of the symptoms described in this case, nor is it the present in this chest X-ray\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHilar lymphadenopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is seen in conditions such as sarcoidosis, tuberculosis, or malignancies affecting the lungs or mediastinum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Edeviated trachea\u003C/strong\u003E can be caused by various conditions such as pneumothorax, large pleural effusion, or mediastinal masses, but it is not present here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile a chest X-ray can provide initial clues, the definitive diagnosis of achalasia typically requires further investigations such as barium swallow studies, manometry, and endoscopy. These tests can confirm the diagnosis and help guide appropriate management, which may include pneumatic dilatation, laparoscopic Heller myotomy, or peroral endoscopic myotomy (POEM).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Achalasia typically presents with progressive dysphagia to both solids and liquids.","A dilated oesophagus on chest X-ray is a characteristic finding in advanced achalasia.","Chest X-ray can be a useful initial investigation in the diagnostic workup of dysphagia."],"references":["Chouw DW, Wu MH. Early detection of recent onset achalasia from a chest radiograph. Internal and Emergency Medicine. 2016;12:407-408. Available at: https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11739-016-1485-8","Adamson J, Altwail M, Jones S. Achalasia: An uncommon presentation with classic imaging. Journal of education and teaching in emergency medicine. 2018. Available at: https://jetem.org/uncommon_achalasia/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34053"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13889"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20827"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20827"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/WC6d4sIQ7ZScbSWseIHltiwMTnGZrZ.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/WC6d4sIQ7ZScbSWseIHltiwMTnGZrZ.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1360,"height":1500}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34053"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-22T15:41:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-22T15:41:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6508"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"4903